- 15 Aug 2016. As of August 10, a total of 1962 laboratory-confirmed Zika virus disease cases have been reported to Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) from 48 U.S. states and the District of Columbia. Of the 1962 cases reported, 1955 are travel associated, 6 were locally acquired mosquito-borne cases [now 42], 22 were sexually transmitted, 6 had Guillain-Barré syndrome, and 1 was laboratory acquired. As of 4 Aug [2016] CDC reports that there are 510 pregnant women with any laboratory evidence of possible Zika virus infection within the U.S. states and the District of Columbia. Texas has 102 Zika virus disease cases.
Source: EpiCore Volunteer Mandy McBroom, UT Southwestern Medical Center

- Florida (Miami) imported. 22 Aug 2016. (conf.) mother infected in Venezuela (Margarita Island) at end of 1st trimester of pregnancy. Baby with no microcephaly but with some brain calcifications and mild retinal changes (can be seen in the video at this URL).
http://www.local10.com/health/zika-virus/south-florida-doctors-treat-baby-girl-born-with-zika-virus

- New York (New York City). 16 Aug 2016. (conf.) 49 pregnant women positive for Zika virus infection, all acquired in countries where transmission was occurring , of these 1 baby born with microcephaly.
http://www.vosizneias.com/247044/2016/08/16/new-york-in-nyc-49-pregnant-women-had-zika-1-baby-born-with-defect/

- Texas (El Paso). 15 Aug 2016. (conf.) one man infected in Florida became ill in Texas - the 1st case of interstate travel of an infected individual in the continental USA.
http://www.jwatch.org/fw111927/2016/08/17/texas-zika-patient-acquired-virus-miami

- Diagnostic for USA. 18 Aug 2016. (reported) On 17 Aug 2016, FDA issued (PDF, 528 KB) an Emergency Use Authorization (EUA) for emergency use of InBios International, Inc.'s ZIKV Detect™ IgM Capture ELISA for the presumptive detection of Zika virus IgM antibodies in human sera. This is the 1st commercially available serological test for Zika available under EUA (the 1st serological test, the CDC Zika MAC-ELISA, was initially authorized for use in February 2016). An EUA is a tool FDA can use to allow the use of certain medical products for emergencies based on scientific data. Including the ZIKV Detect™ IgM Capture ELISA, FDA has issued 9 EUAs for Zika diagnostic tests, as of August 18, 2016.
http://www.fda.gov/MedicalDevices/Safety/EmergencySituations/ucm161496.htm

